    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a great start, thank you. Some of my more skeptical students might argue that this idea is just a way for judges to \"make up\" laws based on their own personal politics rather than actually following the Constitution. How should I address that critique in the lesson? Is there a way to frame it so they understand why this doctrine is necessary despite those criticisms?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can frame substantive due process as a necessary safeguard for minority rights when the majority or Congress has chosen not to act, such as protecting freedom of speech from mob rule before the First Amendment was even ratified. Think of it as a legal \"living room\" where the Constitution interacts with societal changes rather than a static rulebook that ignores evolving human dignity. By explaining that historical shifts in fundamental liberties—like privacy or gender equality—often require judicial interpretation, you show that the courts simply act as the final arbiters when legislation fails to keep up. Ultimately, this doctrine exists to prevent the \"tyranny of the majority\" from trampling on individual rights, ensuring the Constitution remains a living document that protects everyone, not just the loudest voices.",
      "source": "target",
